    <title>This Vision Pro Virtual Boy emulator isn’t fancy, but it gets the job done</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/T3eqrrTvs65Fur-fxyR3Lr9ZRA0=/150x0:1770x1080/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73514216/VirtualFriendVisionProVirtualBoy.0.png" /&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="XJh8F6"&gt;The Vision Pro &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/8/8/24216391/im-seeing-red-and-i-couldnt-be-happier"&gt;got its first Virtual Boy emulator&lt;/a&gt; in an app called &lt;a href="https://apps.apple.com/us/app/virtualfriend-vb-emulator/id6479948317"&gt;VirtualFriend&lt;/a&gt;, finally giving me, a person with an irrational love for Nintendo’s most short-lived console, a chance to play it in immersive 3D once more. The app is also available for iOS and iPadOS, where it’s a virtually identical experience, minus the 3D effect.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="E1fEA9"&gt;The first games I played after downloading VirtualFriend were those I owned as a kid: &lt;em&gt;Red Alarm, Wario Land&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;Mario’s Tennis. &lt;/em&gt;I’m pleased to say that apart from some minor audio glitches in &lt;em&gt;Red Alarm&lt;/em&gt;, the games run well — it’s all just as I remember it. &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;figure class="e-image"&gt;
        
      &lt;cite&gt;GIF: VirtualFriend&lt;/cite&gt;
      &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;The preset “Game Boy” color scheme might be my favorite.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/figcaption&gt;
  &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;p id="uDEQq4"&gt;VirtualFriend supports Bluetooth controllers and...&lt;/p&gt;
